<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911121-0036</DOCNO><DOCID>911121-0036.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Columbia Gas System Inc.:   U.S. Judge Upholds Ruling   On `Take-or-Pay' Contracts</HL><DATE>11/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CG</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)GAS UTILITIES (GAS)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>DELAWARE (DE)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   A U.S. District Court judge upheld a bankruptcy courtruling that allowed Columbia Gas System Inc. to reject itscostly &quot;take-or-pay&quot; natural-gas supply contracts.   In a ruling handed down yesterday in Wilmington, Del.,Judge James L. Latchum denied a motion filed by EnergyDevelopment Corp. claiming the bankruptcy court lacked theauthority to rule on the subject. Energy Development waslisted as the second-largest unsecured creditor of ColumbiaGas's transmission unit, with a claim valued at more than $34million.</LP><TEXT>   To date, the bankruptcy court has allowed Columbia Gas tobreak over 4,500 gas-supply contracts charging prices abovemarket rates. The contracts have been central to thecompany's financial problems and constituted the bulk of a$125 million charge taken in the third quarter.   Columbia Gas sought Chapter 11 protection from creditorsearlier this year, citing the onerous cost of the contracts.</TEXT></DOC>